div1.p:
"Oh, yes; she needn't go out, and Norman will be there to 
amuse her.  I want the boy to take a good long rest this summer; 
he looks desperately thin."

Evidently Norman doubted the truth of his mother's words; 
but, taught by long experience, he refrained from arguing the 
point with her.

She turned to him, eager for his sympathy and indorsement; 
but George Crosby did not reply.  He sank deeper into his chair 
and covered his eyes with his shaking hand.

"No; there's comfort in that thought.  You're not going to 
let her go back to France, are you, Fairfax?" asked the major, 
eying the other man's face anxiously.
